# <%= current_page.data.title %>

Least privilege means giving users and processes only the access they need to perform specific tasks. This helps to protect information and limits the damage if an account is compromised.

All access within the Cabinet Office must be provided on a least-privilege basis. This applies to standard user accounts and individuals who need to switch to high-level 'superuser' access for specific work.

Examples of privileged access include:

* root access  
* updating operating systems  
* performing sudo operations  
* accessing highly sensitive credentials  
* committing to repositories

Use the principle of least privilege to:

* grant access rights based on a person's job role  
* separate day-to-day tasks from security-critical tasks  
* limit the impact of a security breach

## Your team's responsibilities

Your team must follow these requirements to manage access securely.

### **Access management and roles**

* Make users aware of this policy and require them to confirm they understand their access rights  
* Create a process for users to request changes to their access  
* Define specific roles and grant only the permissions needed for those roles  
* Ensure the default option for any user or credential is the lowest possible level of privilege  
* Use a joiners, movers, and leavers process to ensure access is removed when it is no longer needed

### **Technical controls and monitoring**

* Use just-in-time (JIT) access to grant on-demand, time-limited roles or security tokens  
* Set privileged access sessions to expire after 12 hours or when the user logs out  
* Establish an audit trail for all use of privileged access  
* Review privileged access regularly if you cannot implement JIT access  
* Design processes to prevent 'privilege creep', where users accumulate permissions over time

### **Cyber security policy compliance**

External contractors and suppliers must follow Cabinet Office cyber security policies. This includes specific technical and password standards. You can find these documents on the Cabinet Office intranet in the Category: Cyber Policy Compliance Area. If you cannot access the intranet, ask your contract manager or technical lead for these standards.
It's important to recognise opportunities for privilege creep / accumulation and to design in suitable processes for preventing it.

## Examples

For human-readable secrets, such as usernames and passwords, you should use a separate secret or password manager.

If you use the gds-users account to log into AWS, you should use a read-only role by default. Only use an admin role when it is necessary for a specific task. Set the admin session timeout to less than 12 hours.

You should send the audit trail of admin access to the Cyber Security team. Use the Cyber Security Slack channel [\#cyber-security](https://intranet.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/it-data-and-security/cyber-and-information-security-services/) to set up the audit trail.
